value.0: Bloodstains and arcane markings cover the surface of this heavy stone door.
Sturdy wooden planks, topped by iron bands, dissuade travelers from visiting the cemetery.
An ominous tunnel bores its way into the bluff face, leading to some sort of cavern. High-pitched squeals and sounds of combat echo from within.
Marking the grave of some unknown warrior, this greataxe is slowly succumbing to rust.
The vagaries of time have erased all memory of whose head this rusted gravemarker once adorned.
This rusted gravemarker appears to be suffering from years of exposure to the elements.

Dwarven runes are chiseled rough and deep into the stone. A message in the common tongue has been engraved below them by a lighter hand:

"Gunter Blauhart, killed in the battle of Steinfaar's Folly."
This hunched creature overlooks the grounds below. There is a hand-shaped indentation on its haunches, its palm deeply etched with an intricate design.
This small but well-rooted bush provides a reliable handhold for you to climb down to the rock below.

Moths flit about this strange birdcage, as if drawn to a light that isn't there. The cagetop is etched in a feathered pattern, the gathering snow giving it the look of angels' wings.

A bas-relief scene depicts a battle upon the ramparts of an elven citadel. A lone elf, his head thrown back in laughter, holds off the attacking horde. The scene is described in graceful script below:

"Here lie the remains of Fennimore Aelde, last of the Gleeriders."

A handprint, large and coarse, seems to have been pressed into the stone. A brief message is inscribed below:

"Travel on, Sojourner. Travel on..."

Much care and attention went into the carving of this stone. The images of fruits and harvests hearken to some distant land.

"Mother, if only I could bring you back... I pray they do not make you suffer."

This headstone seems newly mounted, its text hastily chiseled. The words seem strange to you, as if you are somehow viewing them out of context.

"Come back to me, my love. This battle is not ended."
